Calculate Brain and Neocortex residuals

brain residuals

# Reduced Major Axis (RMA) regression is called Standard Major Axis (SMA) in lm()
# Have to use SMA because both predicted and predictor variables have error 
library(smatr)
## Loading required package: plyr
## -------------------------------------------------------------------------
## You have loaded plyr after dplyr - this is likely to cause problems.
## If you need functions from both plyr and dplyr, please load plyr first, then dplyr:
## library(plyr); library(dplyr)
## -------------------------------------------------------------------------
## 
## Attaching package: 'plyr'
## 
## The following objects are masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     arrange, count, desc, failwith, id, mutate, rename, summarise,
##     summarize
brainMod <- sma(data=ungs, LogBrain ~ LogBody)
plot(brainMod) # Plot the SMA for funziez

brainRes <- resid(brainMod)
ungs$brainRes <- brainRes
head(ungs)
##                    Species LogBody LogBrain LogNeo Habitat           Diet
## 1            Bos_grunniens    5.40     2.52   2.33    open         Grazer
## 2          Syncerus_caffer    5.88     2.78     NA   mixed         Grazer
## 3     Tragelaphus_scriptus    4.45     2.16     NA   mixed        Browser
## 4       Tragelaphus_spekii    4.69     2.20     NA  closed Grazer/Browser
## 5     Tragelaphus_imberbis    5.16     2.34     NA  closed Grazer/Browser
## 6 Tragelaphus_strepsiceros    5.24     2.53     NA    open Grazer/Browser
##       SocialCode    brainRes
## 1 Harem/Seasonal -0.05416730
## 2    Large mixed -0.07196869
## 3       solitary  0.13564796
## 4 Harem/Seasonal  0.03674726
## 5 Harem/Seasonal -0.09526660
## 6 Harem/Seasonal  0.04843317
plot(brainRes)

shapiro.test(x = ungs$brainRes)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  ungs$brainRes
## W = 0.9576, p-value = 0.0109

p<0.05, Residuals are NOT normally distributed.

neocortex residuals

# Calculate neocortex residuals
neoMod <- sma(data=ungs_neo, LogNeo ~ LogBody)
plot(neoMod) # Plot the SMA again

neoRes <- resid(neoMod)
ungs_neo$neoRes <- neoRes
head(ungs_neo)

Run preliminary ANOVAs

Effect of Habitat

#brainRes
anova(lm(data=ungs, brainRes ~ Habitat))
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: brainRes
##           Df  Sum Sq  Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## Habitat    2 0.02343 0.011713  0.6811 0.5092
## Residuals 75 1.28973 0.017196
# Paper: brainRes was NOT associated with habitat use (p=0.02)

Now account for phylogeny with PGLS

Prepare tree and data first

library(caper)
## Loading required package: ape
## Loading required package: MASS
## Warning: package 'MASS' was built under R version 3.1.3
## 
## Attaching package: 'MASS'
## 
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     select
## 
## Loading required package: mvtnorm
# Load Bininda-Emonds et al. (2007) supertree, with 6617 species of mammals
tree <- read.nexus(file = "http://hompal-stats.wabarr.com/datasets/Bininda_Emonds_correctedDates_FULLPHYLOG.txt")
supertree <- tree[[grep(pattern = "bestDates", names(tree))]] #get the best dates tree
rm(tree)

# Create comparative.data file for brains
supertree_brainz <- comparative.data(phy=supertree, data=ungs, names.col=Species, vcv = TRUE, na.omit = FALSE, warn.dropped = TRUE)
## Warning in comparative.data(phy = supertree, data = ungs, names.col =
## Species, : Data dropped in compiling comparative data object
# Plot to see phylogeny of all species in ungs data (n=89)
plot.phylo(supertree_brainz$phy, cex=0.7, edge.color = "purple", tip.color = "blue", 
           main="Ungulate Phylogeny: \n Brain Residuals", label.offset = 10)
tiplabels(text = round(ungs$brainRes, 2), cex=0.6, frame="none", adj = -0.2)

# Create a separate comparative.data file for the smaller neocortex dataset
supertree_neo <- comparative.data(phy=supertree, data=ungs_neo, names.col=Species, vcv = TRUE, na.omit = FALSE, warn.dropped = TRUE)
## Warning in comparative.data(phy = supertree, data = ungs_neo, names.col =
## Species, : Data dropped in compiling comparative data object
# Plot the tree for species with neocortex data (n=25)
plot.phylo(supertree_neo$phy, cex=0.7, edge.color = "purple", tip.color = "maroon", 
           main="Ungulate Phylogeny: \n Neocortex Residuals", label.offset = 10)
tiplabels(text = round(ungs_neo$neoRes, 2), cex=0.6, frame="none", adj = -0.2)

PGLS: Habitat

brainRes

fit_brainz_Habitat <- pgls(brainRes ~ Habitat, data = supertree_brainz, lambda='ML')
summary(fit_brainz_Habitat)
## 
## Call:
## pgls(formula = brainRes ~ Habitat, data = supertree_brainz, lambda = "ML")
## 
## Residuals:
##       Min        1Q    Median        3Q       Max 
## -0.032177 -0.012477 -0.002657  0.005886  0.035747 
## 
## Branch length transformations:
## 
## kappa  [Fix]  : 1.000
## lambda [ ML]  : 1.000
##    lower bound : 0.000, p = 1.3283e-10
##    upper bound : 1.000, p = 1    
##    95.0% CI   : (0.946, NA)
## delta  [Fix]  : 1.000
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)  -0.095469   0.071311 -1.3388   0.1870
## Habitatmixed  0.060489   0.040836  1.4813   0.1451
## Habitatopen   0.050240   0.037651  1.3344   0.1884
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.01555 on 48 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared: 0.04597, Adjusted R-squared: 0.006223 
## F-statistic: 1.157 on 2 and 48 DF,  p-value: 0.3232
# lambda[ML]=optimized lambda; 
# lower bound=whether opt. lambda is sig different from 0; 
# upper bound=whether opt. lambda is sig different from 1.
paste("optimized lambda = ", fit_brainz_Habitat$param.CI$lambda$opt) # lambda=1
## [1] "optimized lambda =  1"
### Brownian motion (lambda=1, or simply use the corBrownian function). Assumes the trait evolves by Brownian motion and thus that the trait covariance between any pair of taxa decreases linearly with the time (in branch length) since their divergence (and vice versa).

par(mfrow=c(2,2)) # so you can see all 4 plots at once
# get diagnostic plots
plot(fit_brainz_Habitat) 

par(mfrow=c(1,1))#to reset the graphic window to just one graph

Extract partial residuals

library(plotrix) # has an std.error function
detach(package:smatr)
detach(package:plyr) # messes up dplyr summarise

## partial residuals: Habitat
res_brainz_MixHabitat <- data.frame(resid(fit_brainz_Mixed)) # extract all residuals
res_brainz_MixHabitat$Habitat <- supertree_brainz$data$Habitat # add variable as new col
# group by variable and calculate mean and std.error
gres_brainz_MixHabitat <- group_by(res_brainz_MixHabitat, Habitat) %>% 
  summarize(mean=mean(resid.fit_brainz_Mixed.), se=std.error(resid.fit_brainz_Mixed.))

## partial residuals: Diet
res_brainz_MixDiet <- data.frame(resid(fit_brainz_Mixed))
res_brainz_MixDiet$Diet <- supertree_brainz$data$Diet
gres_brainz_MixDiet <- group_by(res_brainz_MixDiet, Diet) %>% 
  summarize(mean=mean(resid.fit_brainz_Mixed.), se=std.error(resid.fit_brainz_Mixed.))

## partial residuals: Sociality
res_brainz_MixSocial <- data.frame(resid(fit_brainz_Mixed))
res_brainz_MixSocial$Social <- supertree_brainz$data$SocialCode
gres_brainz_MixSocial <- group_by(res_brainz_MixSocial, Social) %>% 
  summarize(mean=mean(resid.fit_brainz_Mixed.), se=std.error(resid.fit_brainz_Mixed.))

Plot PRs: Habitat

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(data=gres_brainz_MixHabitat, aes(x=Habitat, y=mean, fill=Habitat)) + 
  geom_bar(stat="identity", position = "identity") + theme_classic() + geom_hline(yintercept=0) +
  labs(title="Brain Residuals ~ Habitat", y="partial brain residuals") + 
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mean, ymax=mean+se), width=0.25) + 
  geom_text(aes(y=-.004, x=1, label=paste("n=", count(filter(ungs, Habitat == "closed"))))) +
  geom_text(aes(y=-.004, x=2, label=paste("n=", count(filter(ungs, Habitat == "mixed"))))) + 
  geom_text(aes(y=-.004, x=3, label=paste("n=", count(filter(ungs, Habitat == "open")))))
